1. Build and Install Lua 5.4.6
Since the system lacked a Lua interpreter, we built one from source to power your Neovim configuration.


cd ~
wget https://www.lua.org/ftp/lua-5.4.6.tar.gz
tar -zxf lua-5.4.6.tar.gz
cd lua-5.4.6
make linux
cp src/lua ~/.local/bin/
cp src/luac ~/.local/bin/
chmod +x ~/.local/bin/lua ~/.local/bin/luac
cd ~
rm -rf lua-5.4.6 lua-5.4.6.tar.gz
2. Install Static Clang-Format
This version bypasses the libtinfo.so.5 error by using a fully static build.


wget https://github.com/muttleyxd/clang-tools-static-binaries/releases/latest/download/clang-format-18_linux-amd64 -O ~/.local/bin/clang-format
chmod +x ~/.local/bin/clang-format
3. Install Standalone Clangd (LSP)
This provides the IntelliSense and code navigation for C++ without requiring Mason's automated installers.


wget https://github.com/clangd/clangd/releases/download/18.1.3/clangd-linux-18.1.3.zip
unzip clangd-linux-18.1.3.zip
mv clangd_18.1.3/bin/clangd ~/.local/bin/
chmod +x ~/.local/bin/clangd
rm -rf clangd_18.1.3 clangd-linux-18.1.3.zip
4. Update Shell Environment
Add these to your ~/.bashrc to ensure your local binaries and Lua paths are prioritized.


export PATH="$HOME/.local/bin:$PATH"
export LUA_PATH="$HOME/.local/share/lua/?.lua;$HOME/.local/share/lua/?/init.lua;;"
Apply changes with: source ~/.bashrc

5. Mandatory Neovim Clean Reset
Run these commands to remove the incompatible "0.11" plugin versions and force Neovim to install the pinned versions defined in your init.lua.


rm -rf ~/.local/share/nvim/lazy
rm -rf ~/.local/state/nvim/lazy
